@astrofrog @larrybradley @bsipocz Do you think we should support 32-bit machines for photutils?

I'm -1 because it's extremely rare these days and we don't have developers / continuous integration using 32-bit, so it's annoying to support.

I've been bitten many times where I accidentally used 32-bit images and got (sometimes completely, sometimes slightly) incorrect results when summing over many pixels, so for Gammapy I've adopted a ["do computations with `float64`" policy](https://gammapy.readthedocs.org/en/latest/development/index.html#float-data-type-32-bit-or-64-bit)

@rhyolight I don't have a strong opinion on this anymore. 

The good thing about the current state is that the documentation is right there for a person looking at the python code. They don't have to go to another C++ repository and understand C++. (This issue was actually created when C++ and Python were in the same repository so it was a bit easier - now users have to go to a separate repository.)

The bad thing is that there is duplication, so we have to be careful to keep the two in sync.

@mmalohlava the name of the `egg` file is automatically set by the method generating it and it automatically adds the `-py2.7` or `-py3.5` suffix depending on which Python version was added. Whether or not we can override this behaviour to remove the suffix is a good question, haven't looked into it. Maybe @jakubhava knows? So if you run `./gradlew clean build` from a terminal which has Python set to 3.5 and then try to run `pysparkling` it won't work because the script has hardcoded `2.7` and the egg file will have the suffix `3.5`.

The line `eggs file("${project.buildDir}/dist/h2o_pysparkling_${version.substring(0, version.lastIndexOf('.'))}-${version.replace("-SNAPSHOT","")}-py${PYTHON_VERSION}.egg").getAbsoluteFile()` does not decide the `egg` name, it just adds the already generated `egg` file to the `eggs` custom gradle configuration which we are using in python tests.

tl;dr: I agree that removing the `py` suffix is a good idea (as long as we plan on making both versions compatible) but I'm not sure how to; I agree, it shouldn't say "removing" but "setting the proper python version for the egg file dependency".

It does not seem a special need, but a common behavior. I never saw a image with a cursor as a text selection. But this is what occurs with font awesome icon on Firefox.
This can be resolved with a CSS rule; and when icon is inside a link, as showed by @ramonakira, a simple second rule is used.

```
.fa {
    cursor: default;
}
a .fa:hover {
    cursor: pointer;
}
```
Icons always display as it on all sites.
I can add it to my css to customize font awesome, but I think that it could (should) be present base in font awesome.

