@zed Yes, tzlocal is a different module from pytz, though, and what it does is figure out what time zone your system is in, then takes the current UTC time and gives you the time in the system time zone. This is a little different from what `tz.tzlocal()` does.

Arguably, we should be duplicating the functionality of the `tzlocal` module, but if you actually take a look at `tzlocal`, you'll see it's not exactly a trivial undertaking (as I said above).

Of course, apparently per #112, we're not even getting it right even when we *know* the time zone we're in, but I suspect that if we fix #112, it still won't fix this issue.

