@Gr3yh0und, the [TinyDTLS site](https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/iot.tinydtls/governance) indicates:

> The cipher suites supported by tinydtls are limited to TLS_PSK_WITH_AES_128_CCM_8 and TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_128_CCM_8 that are mandatory-to-implement for CoAP.

Unfortunately, Thread 1.1 requires an EC-JPAKE cipher suite.

The important thing would be to do it without adding undue computation/code bloat to the general case (i.e. types which don't care about being stored in a numpy container).

This feature could potentially be implemented by creating a function that appends a new implicit conversion to the type's ``implicit_conversions`` list. The entries of that list are functions which take a ``py::object`` that can't be handled by the associated invocation of ``type_caster_generic::load()`` and return one that can be handled. All implementations currently involve making a copy, but it would be possible to add conversions that return a different view of the original data.

In this particular case, the implicit conversion should check that the argument is a ``py::array`` with the expected dtype.

Then I guess, you'd do something like
```
object inst(PyType_GenericAlloc(tinfo->type, 0), false);
auto wrapper = (instance<void> *) inst.ptr();
wrapper->value = <pointer to py::array contents>;
wrapper->owned = false;
detail::keep_alive_impl(inst, <py::array instance>);
internals.registered_instances.emplace(wrapper->value, inst.ptr());
return inst.release();
```

where ``tinfo`` is a pointer to pybind11's internal record of the type.

This is the following example:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <list>
#include <memory>

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

std::list<std::unique_ptr<int>> foo(void) {
    std::list<std::unique_ptr<int>> a;
    for (uint32_t i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
        a.emplace_back(new int(i));
    }
    return a;
}

void init_module(pybind11::module &m) {

  m.def("foo", &foo);
}

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(myModule) {

  pybind11::module myModule("myModule");

  init_module(myModule);

  return myModule.ptr();
}


int main()
{
  std::list<std::unique_ptr<int>> bar = foo();
  for (const auto& i : bar) {
      std::cout << std::to_string(*i) << std::endl;
  }
}
```

